Democratic Senator Barack Obama, a vocal critic of the Iraq war and 2008 presidential hopeful, emphasized the need for top-notch care for wounded soldiers.
The Washington Post uncovered neglect of outpatients at Walter Reed, prompting investigations and promises of accountability from Defense Secretary Robert Gates.
The Army pledged to address substandard living conditions and bureaucratic inefficiencies.
Congressional leaders called for urgent reforms to aid soldiers stuck in limbo.
Despite criticism, Army officials defended their actions and vowed to streamline medical evaluations.
An independent panel was appointed to review care processes at Walter Reed and the National Naval Medical Center.
